2026-06-15 | Minimum Cost to Buy Exactly W Kg Oranges

	Question
Return the minimum cost, or -1 if it is impossible.
	Key Insight
This is a classic Unbounded Knapsack problem.
For every available packet:
		weight = i + 1
		cost = cost[i]
We can use that packet multiple times.
Let:
		dp[x]
	be the minimum cost required to buy exactly x kg.
Transition:
		dp[x]
		=
		min(dp[x],
		    dp[x - packetWeight] + packetCost)
	Approach
1.	Create dp array of size w + 1.
2.	Initialize:
		dp[0] = 0
		all others = INF
3.	For every available packet:
		weight = i + 1
4.	Run unbounded knapsack transition.
5.	If dp[w] remains INF:
		return -1
6.	Else return dp[w].
	Time Complexity
	O(n × w)
	Space Complexity
	O(w)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumCost(vector<int>& cost, int w) {
        const int INF = 1e9;
        vector<int> dp(w + 1, INF);
        dp[0] = 0;
        int n = cost.size();
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if(cost[i] == -1)
                continue;
            int weight = i + 1;
            for(int j = weight; j <= w; j++) {
                dp[j] = min(dp[j],
                            dp[j - weight] + cost[i]);
            }
        }
        return dp[w] == INF ? -1 : dp[w];
    }
};
	Key Insight
The problem is identical to making a target weight using unlimited copies of available packet sizes while minimizing cost. Therefore it is a direct application of the Unbounded Knapsack Dynamic Programming pattern.
